just a one-time setup but an iterative process aimed at optimizing the <a h=
ref=3D"https://www.ultralytics.com/glossary/machine-learning-ml">machine le=
arning</a> model's performance metrics, such as accuracy, precision, and re=
call. In the context of Ultralytics YOLO, these hyperparameters could range=
 from learning rate to architectural details, such as the number of layers =
or types of activation functions used. <a href=3D"https://platform.ultralyt=
ics.com/">Ultralytics Platform</a> also supports <a href=3D"https://docs.ul=
tralytics.com/platform/train/cloud-training/">cloud training</a> with confi=
gurable hyperparameters and real-time metrics tracking.</p><p align=3D"cent=
er"><br><iframe allow=3D"accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypte=
d-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture; web-share" allowfullscreen=3D"" fra=
meborder=3D"0" height=3D"405" loading=3D"lazy" src=3D"cid:frame-16690CAFF20=
078C33A9CB00DF1217C1B@mhtml.blink" width=3D"720" title=3D"YouTube video pla=
yer"></iframe><br><strong>Watch:</strong> How to Tune Hyperparameters for B=
etter Model Performance =F0=9F=9A=80
</p><h3 id=3D"what-are-hyperparameters">What are Hyperparameters?</h3><p>Hy=
perparameters are high-level, structural settings for the algorithm. They a=
re set prior to the training phase and remain constant during it. Here are =
some commonly tuned hyperparameters in Ultralytics YOLO:</p><ul><li><strong=
>Learning Rate</strong> <code data-wg-notranslate=3D"">lr0</code>: Determin=
es the step size at each iteration while moving towards a minimum in the <a=
 href=3D"https://www.ultralytics.com/glossary/loss-function">loss function<=
/a>.</li><li><strong><a href=3D"https://www.ultralytics.com/glossary/batch-=
size">Batch Size</a></strong> <code data-wg-notranslate=3D"">batch</code>: =
Number of images processed simultaneously in a forward pass.</li><li><stron=
g>Number of <a href=3D"https://www.ultralytics.com/glossary/epoch">Epochs</=
a></strong> <code data-wg-notranslate=3D"">epochs</code>: An epoch is one c=
omplete forward and backward pass of all the training examples.</li><li><st=
rong>Architecture Specifics</strong>: Such as channel counts, number of lay=
ers, types of activation functions, etc.</li></ul><p align=3D"center"><img =
alt=3D"Hyperparameter optimization search space visualization" src=3D"https=
://cdn.jsdelivr.net/gh/ultralytics/assets@main/docs/hyperparameter-tuning-v=
isual.avif" width=3D"640"></p><p>For a full list of augmentation hyperparam=
eters used in YOLO26 please refer to the <a href=3D"https://docs.ultralytic=
s.com/usage/cfg/#augmentation-settings">configurations page</a>.</p><h3 id=
=3D"genetic-evolution-and-mutation">Genetic Evolution and Mutation</h3><p>U=
ltralytics YOLO uses <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Genetic_algor=
ithm">genetic algorithms</a> to optimize hyperparameters. Genetic algorithm=
s are inspired by the mechanism of natural selection and genetics.</p><ul><=
li><strong>Crossover</strong>: Each iteration combines genes from up to nin=
e of the highest-fitness configurations seen so far, using BLX-=CE=B1 cross=
over with fitness-weighted parent selection.</li><li><strong>Mutation</stro=
ng>: The recombined candidate is then perturbed by a log-normal multiplicat=
ive factor applied to each hyperparameter (with probability 0.5 per paramet=
er). The mutation strength sigma decays linearly from 0.2 to 0.1 over the f=
irst 300 iterations, so the algorithm explores broadly early and refines as=
 it converges. Iteration 1 has no parents to crossover from and uses the de=
fault training hyperparameters as a baseline.</li></ul><h2 id=3D"preparing-=
for-hyperparameter-tuning">Preparing for Hyperparameter Tuning</h2><p>Befor=
e you begin the tuning process, it's important to:</p><ol><li><strong>Ident=
ify the Metrics</strong>: Determine the metrics you will use to evaluate th=
e model's performance. This could be AP50, F1-score, or others.</li><li><st=
rong>Set the Tuning Budget</strong>: Define how much computational resource=
s you're willing to allocate. Hyperparameter tuning can be computationally =
intensive.</li></ol><h2 id=3D"steps-involved">Steps Involved</h2><h3 id=3D"=
initialize-hyperparameters">Initialize Hyperparameters</h3><p>Start with a =
reasonable set of initial hyperparameters. This could either be the default=
 hyperparameters set by Ultralytics YOLO or something based on your domain =
knowledge or previous experiments.</p><h3 id=3D"mutate-hyperparameters">Mut=
ate Hyperparameters</h3><p>Use the <code data-wg-notranslate=3D"">_mutate</=
code> method to produce a new set of hyperparameters based on the existing =
set. The <a href=3D"https://docs.ultralytics.com/reference/engine/tuner/">T=
uner class</a> handles this process automatically.</p><h3 id=3D"train-model=
">Train Model</h3><p>Training is performed using the mutated set of hyperpa=
rameters. The training performance is then assessed using your chosen metri=
cs.</p><h3 id=3D"evaluate-model">Evaluate Model</h3><p>Use metrics like AP5=
0, F1-score, or custom metrics to evaluate the model's performance. The <a =
href=3D"https://docs.ultralytics.com/modes/val/">evaluation process</a> hel=
ps determine if the current hyperparameters are better than previous ones.<=
/p><h3 id=3D"log-results">Log Results</h3><p>It's crucial to log both the p=
erformance metrics and the corresponding hyperparameters for future referen=
ce. Ultralytics YOLO automatically saves these results in NDJSON format.</p=
><h3 id=3D"repeat">Repeat</h3><p>The process is repeated until either the s=
et number of iterations is reached or the performance metric is satisfactor=
y. Each iteration builds upon the knowledge gained from previous runs.</p><=
